The organiser of the Sustainability, Enterprise and Responsibility (SERAS) Awards at the weekend in Lagos adjudged Ebenezer Onyeagwu, Zenith Bank’s Group Managing Director/CE, as CEO of the Year.The organiser gave reasons to why, Onyeagwu was selected from several reasons among these practices were a robust Environmental and Social Management System for screening credit facilities and continued investment in social initiatives. The measures taken by the bank, the organiser said, support the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs). Zenith Bank has also joined 131 other lenders from across the globe as a founding signatory to the United Nations Environment Programme Finance Initiative (UNEP FI) Principles for Responsible Banking. READ ALSO THIS: ZENITH BANK EMERGES BEST BANK IN NIGERIA SAYS THE GLOBAL FINANCE WORLD’S BEST BANKS AWARDS 2020 The judges found Onyeagwu worthy for his commitment to the promotion of sustainability and responsible business practices in Nigeria, by his frontal leadership of sustainability in Zenith Bank, thereby enabling best industry practices in the banking sector, and for his passion to reduce carbon emissions in the bank’s operations. Zenith Bank also emerged winner in two other categories at the awards, carting home the awards for “Best Company in Promotion of Good Health and Well-Being and Best Company in Promotion of Gender Equality and Women Empowerment” . Zenith Bank was adjudged winner in the category for the Best Company in Promotion of Gender Equality and Women Empowerment for its Z-Woman initiative which offers credit facilities to women-owned businesses at single-digit interest rate and for a gender-balanced workforce (about 49.80 per cent female and 50.20 per cent male). READ ALSO THIS: Zenith Bank Manager pleaded not guilty to three counts of conspiracy and fraud of N179, 498 million Also Zenith Bank emerged winner among five finalists for the Best Company in Promotion of Good Health and Well-Being Category for donating N1 billion in support of efforts to address the COVID-19 pandemic in Nigeria, donation of N200 million towards Lagos State Government’s efforts to provide relief to the victims of the Abule-Ado pipeline explosion, and for spending over N300 million in 2019 to support various healthcare initiatives across the country.